# part 5: permissions
SELinux must be running in the Enforcing mode (permanent even after reboot).

sestatus/getenforce              # Check current SELinux status and mode
setenforce 1                     # Set SELinux to enforcing mode temporarily (runtime)
vim /etc/selinux/config          # Edit SELinux config file to make enforcing permanent Change SELINUX=permissive to SELINUX=enforcing and save the file
systemctl reboot
sestatus/getenforce              # Verify that SELinux is now enforcing permanently

notes:
SELinux (Security-Enhanced Linux) is a mandatory access control system that adds an extra layer of security to Linux, which is stronger than regular Linux permissions.
Normal Linux permissions: control who can read/write/execute files.
SELinux adds another layer: controls what programs/processes are allowed to do, regardless of Linux permissions.
Enforcing blocks access, Permissive logs only, Disabled turns SELinux off.
